This paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category as it deals with personalized search and recommendations on networks. It could also belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category as it mentions social networks and user-item networks. The paper also presents new algorithms for estimating random walk scores, which is a common problem in the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Additionally, the paper presents theoretical analysis, which is a common feature of papers in the Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the paper could also belong to the Social and Behavioral Sciences (cs.SOC) sub-category as it deals with social networks and personalized search.
